{"parse":{"title":"clapper","pageid":3675,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Clapper}}\n==English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈklæpɚ/|a=GA}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-clapper.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{rhymes|en|æpə(ɹ)|s=2}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|en|:af|clap|-er<id:agent noun>|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# One who [[clap]]s; a person who [[applaud]]s by clapping the hands.\n# {{senseid|en|bell}} An object so suspended inside a [[bell]] that it may hit the bell and cause it to ring; a [[clanger]] or [[tongue]].\n# A wooden mechanical device used as a [[scarecrow]]; bird-scaring [[rattle]], a wind-rattle or a wind-clapper.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1896|author=Sabine Baring-Gould|title=Arminell, a social romance|section=[[Wikisource:Arminell, a social romance/Chapter 37|Ch. 37]]\n|passage=\"Sir, sir! folks' tongues go like the '''clappers''' in the fields to drive away the blackbirds. A very little wind makes 'em rattle wonderfully.\"}}\n# A [[clapstick]] {{gl|musical instrument}}.\n# {{lb|en|sewing}} A [[pounding block]].\n# The [[chattering damsel]] of a [[mill]].\n# {{lb|en|ice hockey}} A [[slapshot]]\n# {{lb|en|cinematography}} The hinged part of a [[clapperboard]], used to synchronise images and soundtrack, or the clapperboard itself.\n# {{lb|en|slang}} A person's [[tongue]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1683|author=S. P.|title=The Dutch Rogue, Or, Gusman of Amsterdam|page=238\n|passage=''Emilia'' 'tis true could use her '''clapper''' with great Dexterity, but he had the same advantages against ''her'', which this had against ''him''; ''Olimpia'' <!--space not in original, inserted due to wiki bold formatting problems-->'s Tongue was also well hung but she ever had reason on her side, which he with reason could never either blame or oppose, and by both these came his Fortune: {{...}}}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|musical instrument}} {{l|en|clapstick}}, {{l|en|musicstick}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|en|clapperboard|clapperboy<!--\"clapper bridge\" is not derived from \"clapper\"-->|clapperclaw|clapperless|clapper-loader|clapper talk|clapper-valve|handclapper|like the clappers|clapper board|clapper rail|happy clapper}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|the tongue of a bell}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|լեզվակ}}, {{t+|hy|զանգալեզվակ}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|bazhoulenn|f}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|ези́к|m}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|batall|m}}\n* Czech: {{t|cs|srdce zvonu}}, {{t+|cs|srdce}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|klepel|m}}, {{t+|nl|bengel|m}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|koro}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kieli}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|batail|m}}, {{t+|fr|battant|m}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|batocj|m}}, {{t|fur|banducel|m}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|badalo|m}}, {{t|gl|batel|m}}\n* Gallurese: {{t|sdn|battaddólu}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Klöppel|m}}, {{t|de|Schwengel|m}}\n*: Alemannic German: {{t|gsw|Challe|m}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|עִנְבָּל|m|tr=inbal}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|harangnyelv}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|kólfur|m}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|boschrann|m}}, {{t|ga|teanga cloig|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|battaglio}}, {{t+|it|batacchio|m}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|جرس|tr=jaras}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|serce|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|badalo|m}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|limbă|f}}\n* Russian: {{t|ru|[[язы́к]] ([[колокол|ко́локола]])|m}}\n* Sardinian: {{t|sc|batazu|m}}, {{t|sc|batarzu|m}}, {{t|sc|batalzu|m}}, {{t|sc|batàgliu|m}}, {{t|sc|antarzu|m}}, {{t|sc|entazu|m}}\n*: Campidanese: {{t|sc|tratallu}}\n*: Logudorese: {{t|sc|battazu}}, {{t|sc|piròne}}, {{t|sc|limbèddu}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{t|dsb|palica|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|badajo|m}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|kläpp|c}}\n* Venetan: {{t|vec|batocio|m}}, {{t|vec|batòcolo|m}}, {{t|vec|batòc|m}}, {{t|vec|batidor|m}}, {{t|vec|batibèƚo|m}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|bata|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|rattle}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|кречетало|n}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|řehtačka|f}}, {{t+|cs|klapačka|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|ratel|m}}, {{t+|nl|klapper|m}}, {{t+|nl|klepper|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|räikkä}}\n* Greek:\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|κρέμβαλα|n-p}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|kereplő}}, {{t+|hu|szélkelep}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|ngutu rakiraki}}, {{t|mi|pākōkō}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|трещо́тка|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To ring a [[bell]] by pulling a rope attached to the clapper.\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=A rudimentary treatise on clocks and watches and bells|author=Baron Edmund Beckett Grimthorpe|year=1903|passage=It is still necessary to warn clergymen against allowing the lazy and pernicious practice of ''''clappering''',' ''i.e.'' tying the bell-rope to the clapper, and pulling it instead of the bell.}}\n# To make a [[repetitive]] clapping sound; to [[clatter]].\n# Of birds, to repeatedly strike the mandibles together.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|clapperdudgeon}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{ety|en|:bor|fr:clapier|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[rabbit]] [[burrow]].\n#* {{RQ:Tusser Good Husbandrie|year=1810|passage=Poore cunnie so bagged, <br>Is soone overlagged <br>Plash burrow, set clapper, <br>For dog is a snapper}}\n\n===References===\n{{R:Webster 1913}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l|en|clapper bridge}} {{i|has a distinct etymology}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-clapper.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Lyokoï-clapper.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-WikiLucas00-clapper.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Jérémy-Günther-Heinz Jähnick-clapper.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Somain>>)}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{fr-verb}}\n\n# to [[click]] (the tongue)\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{fr-conj-auto}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|fr|clappement}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}"}}